<DOC><DOCNO> AP891006-0145 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1641EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i BC-Salvador     10-06 0246</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Salvador,0256</SECOND><HEAD>URGENT</HEAD><HEAD>Salvadoran Activists Agree To Release Embassy Hostages</HEAD><DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Leftist activists ended their28-hour takeover of the Costa Rican Embassy on Friday, releasingthe 12 hostages they held to protest against President AlfredoCristiani's rightist government.   A total of 12 hostages and 20 members of the Federation ofCommittees of Mothers and Relatives of Political Prisoners wereevacuated in six International Red Cross vehicles around 1:30 p.m.,watched by journalists.   The reporters were kept 30 yards away by police and not allowedto talk to the evacuees. None of the activists nor the one CostaRican diplomat and 11 Salvadoran embassy employees appeared to behurt.   Government spokesman Mauricio Sandoval told reporters some ofthe activists left weapons ``inside the (embassy) offices orhidden,'' because they carried none when they boarded the Red Crossvehicles.   The activists have insisted they were not armed, but Costa Ricandiplomats disputed that.   Sandoval said the hostages were being taken to Red Crossheadquarters in San Salvador, where they would be undergo medicalchecks before being sent home, and the activists returned to thefederation office.   He said the Salvadoran government could eventually file chargesagainst some of those involved in the takeover.   The federation has been protesting for the past eight years thekidnapping and killing of suspected leftists by rightist deathsquads. The decade-old civil war has killed more than 70,000people, between death-squad victims and casualties of the fighting.</TEXT></DOC>